<dl id="n12054b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12054b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12054b"> 54(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> not eat salmon more / than 3 times / a week</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Parmi ces poissons, mulets, bars, plies, soles, esturgeons, maquereaux, etc., le saumon de la baie du Mont Saint-Michel est justement renomm&eacute;. On a affirm&eacute; (mais jamais nous n&apos;avons trouv&eacute; preuve certaine de ce fait), qu&apos;avant 1825, le saumon &eacute;tait tellement commun dans le pays que les domestiques des fermes de la c&ocirc;te normande imposaient &agrave; leurs ma&icirc;tres, en se gageant la condition expresse de ne pas manger de saumon plus de trois fois par semaine. <br><font color="green">[Amongst the fish, mullets, sea bass, plaice, sole, sturgeon, mackerel, etc the salmon of the bay of Mont Saint-Michel was rightly famous. It has been claimed (but we have not been able to find definite proof of the fact) that before 1825 salmon was so common in the country that domestics in the farms on the Normandy coast forced on their masters when they applied for a position the condition <mark>not to have them eat salmon more than three times a week</mark>.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 79</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
